---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import QuoteForm from '../../components/QuoteForm.astro';

const defined_title = "How to Import Guar Gum to the USA";
const defined_description = "Complete guide to importing guar gum powder from India to the United States. FDA GRAS status, food and industrial grade specifications, HS codes, and sourcing from Rajasthan.";

const breadcrumbItems = [
  { label: "Guides", href: "/guides" },
  { label: "Import Guar Gum to USA" },
];

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://origindirectgroup.com/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Guides", "item": "https://origindirectgroup.com/guides" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Import Guar Gum to USA" },
  ],
};

const howToSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "HowTo",
  "name": "How to Import Guar Gum to the USA",
  "description": "Step-by-step guide for importing guar gum powder from India to the United States for food and industrial applications.",
  "step": [
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 1, "name": "Find an Indian guar gum supplier", "text": "Source from processors in Rajasthan, India's guar gum production hub." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 2, "name": "Request samples", "text": "Test for viscosity, mesh size, moisture, protein, and microbiological safety." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 3, "name": "Agree on terms", "text": "Negotiate pricing per MT, grade (food/industrial/fast-hydration), and specs." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 4, "name": "Prepare documentation", "text": "Obtain FSSAI certificate, COA, phytosanitary certificate." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 5, "name": "Arrange shipping", "text": "Ship from Mundra or JNPT to US ports. Transit 22-30 days." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 6, "name": "Clear US customs", "text": "File ISF, FDA prior notice, pass FDA and CBP inspections." },
    { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 7, "name": "Receive and distribute", "text": "Inspect quality, distribute to food manufacturers and oil/gas industry." },
  ],
};
---

<Layout title={defined_title} description={defined_description} structuredData={[breadcrumbSchema, howToSchema]}>
  <section class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />

      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
        How to Import Guar Gum to the USA
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        The United States is the world's largest importer of guar gum, consuming approximately 200,000-300,000 metric tons annually. India produces over 80% of the world's guar, with Rajasthan accounting for 70% of Indian production. Guar gum is used across two major segments: food (as a thickener, stabilizer, and emulsifier in ice cream, bakery products, sauces, and dairy) and industrial (as a viscosifier in oil and gas drilling, mining, textiles, and paper). Importing directly from Indian processors gives US buyers access to the full range of grades at competitive prices. This guide covers both food-grade and industrial-grade guar gum imports.
      </p>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-700">

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Step-by-Step Import Process</h2>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 1: Find an Indian Guar Gum Supplier</h3>
        <p>
          India's guar gum industry is concentrated in Rajasthan, with major processing clusters in Jodhpur, Jaipur, Sri Ganganagar, and Bikaner. Gujarat (Kutch region) is a secondary production hub. The industry ranges from large integrated companies processing 100+ MT/day to smaller regional mills. For food-grade guar gum, look for suppliers with: BRC/FSSC 22000 certified facilities, FDA FCE/SID registration (for low-acid canned food applications), Kosher and Halal certifications (standard for US food market), and the ability to produce fast-hydration and derivatized grades. For oil and gas grade, capacity, consistency, and viscosity specifications matter most. Origin Direct works with established guar gum processors across Rajasthan, offering food-grade, industrial-grade, and specialty grades.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 2: Request Samples and Test Quality</h3>
        <p>
          Guar gum specifications vary significantly by grade and application:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Viscosity</strong> - The most important specification. Measured in centipoise (cps) using a Brookfield viscometer at 1% solution. Food grade: 3,500-5,500 cps typical. Industrial/oil field: 4,500-6,500+ cps. Higher viscosity = higher quality = higher price.</li>
          <li><strong>Mesh size</strong> - Food grade: 200 mesh (74 microns). Fast-hydration: 200 mesh. Industrial: 100-200 mesh.</li>
          <li><strong>Moisture</strong> - Max 12%.</li>
          <li><strong>Protein</strong> - Max 5% for food grade. Lower protein = cleaner solution.</li>
          <li><strong>Ash</strong> - Max 1% for food grade.</li>
          <li><strong>Acid-insoluble residue</strong> - Max 7% (indicates guar hull content).</li>
          <li><strong>pH</strong> - 5.5-7.0 for food grade.</li>
          <li><strong>Microbiological</strong> - Total plate count max 5,000 CFU/g, E. coli absent, Salmonella absent in 25g, yeast and mold max 500 CFU/g.</li>
          <li><strong>Heavy metals</strong> - Lead max 2 ppm, arsenic max 3 ppm (per FDA specifications for food additives).</li>
          <li><strong>Dioxin/PCBs</strong> - May be required for EU-destined product but increasingly requested by US buyers too.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 3: Agree on Commercial Terms</h3>
        <p>
          Pricing per MT, FOB Mundra/JNPT or CIF US port. Guar gum prices are notoriously volatile, heavily influenced by oil and gas drilling activity (which drives industrial demand) and Indian crop conditions. Between 2011-2013, guar gum prices spiked from $1,000/MT to over $30,000/MT due to US shale gas boom. Currently prices are more stable but still fluctuate significantly. Payment: L/C at sight for first orders. Contracts: specify viscosity (minimum guarantee), mesh, grade, packaging (25 kg multiwall paper bags, 50 kg PP bags, or 1 MT bulk bags), and delivery window. For oil and gas applications, annual supply contracts with quarterly pricing adjustments are common.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 4: Supplier Prepares Documentation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>FSSAI Export Certificate</strong> - For food-grade guar gum.</li>
          <li><strong>Certificate of Analysis</strong> - Comprehensive lab report covering viscosity, mesh, moisture, protein, ash, pH, and microbiological parameters.</li>
          <li><strong>Certificate of Origin</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Commercial Invoice and Packing List</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Bill of Lading</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Phytosanitary Certificate</strong> - From India's plant protection authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Kosher Certificate</strong> - If required. Most US food manufacturers need this.</li>
          <li><strong>Halal Certificate</strong> - Increasingly requested.</li>
          <li><strong>Non-GMO Declaration</strong> - Guar is not commercially available in GMO varieties, but buyers often request this statement.</li>
          <li><strong>Allergen Declaration</strong> - Guar gum is not a major allergen but should be declared if processed in a facility that handles allergens.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 5: Arrange Shipping</h3>
        <p>
          Guar gum ships in 20ft containers, approximately 18-20 MT per container in bags on pallets. Loading ports: Mundra Port (Gujarat, closest to Rajasthan processors), JNPT/Nhava Sheva (Mumbai), Kandla. US destination ports: Port of Houston (for oil and gas customers in Texas), Port Newark (for food manufacturers in the Northeast), Port of Long Beach (for West Coast). Transit: Mundra to Houston 25-30 days, Mundra to Newark 22-28 days, Mundra to Long Beach 20-25 days. Guar gum is hygroscopic (absorbs moisture). Use container liners and desiccant strips, especially for summer shipments.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 6: Clear US Customs</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ISF 10+2</strong> - Filed 24 hours before departure.</li>
          <li><strong>FDA Prior Notice</strong> - Required for food-grade guar gum.</li>
          <li><strong>FDA Classification</strong> - Guar gum is GRAS (Generally Recognized As Safe) per 21 CFR 184.1339 for food use. It is also approved under the FCC (Food Chemicals Codex) specifications.</li>
          <li><strong>FDA Examination</strong> - FDA may sample guar gum for Salmonella, heavy metals, and filth. Having a clean import history and comprehensive COA reduces detention risk.</li>
          <li><strong>FSVP Compliance</strong> - Required for food-grade imports.</li>
          <li><strong>CBP Entry</strong> - Standard customs entry.</li>
          <li><strong>Duty</strong> - Guar gum (HS 1302.32.00): MFN duty rate is free. Guar gum enters the US duty-free.</li>
          <li><strong>For industrial grade</strong> - If importing for oil and gas use, FDA requirements do not apply since the product is not entering the food supply. However, still requires CBP entry and ISF.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step 7: Receive and Distribute</h3>
        <p>
          Inspect: verify viscosity (the critical specification), mesh size, moisture, and pull samples for lab analysis. For food-grade, ensure your receiving and storage facilities meet food safety standards. US distribution channels: food manufacturers (ice cream, bakery, dairy, sauces, pet food), oil and gas service companies (Halliburton, Schlumberger, Baker Hughes, and smaller regional companies), mining and drilling operations, textile and paper industries, and pharmaceutical companies.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Key Documents Required</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>FDA Prior Notice (food-grade)</li>
          <li>ISF 10+2</li>
          <li>CBP Entry Summary</li>
          <li>Certificate of Analysis</li>
          <li>FSSAI Export Certificate (food-grade)</li>
          <li>Phytosanitary Certificate</li>
          <li>Commercial Invoice and Packing List</li>
          <li>Bill of Lading</li>
          <li>Kosher/Halal Certificates (if applicable)</li>
          <li>FSVP documentation (food-grade)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">HS Codes and Duty Rates</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>1302.32.00</strong> - Mucilages and thickeners derived from guar seeds. MFN Duty: Free.</li>
          <li><strong>0713.90.80</strong> - Guar seeds (dried leguminous vegetables). MFN Duty: Free.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For the full HS code reference, see our <a href="/resources/hs-codes" class="text-brand-700 underline hover:text-brand-600">HS Code Directory</a>.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Common Pitfalls to Watch Out For</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Viscosity shortfall</strong> - The most common complaint. Suppliers may test viscosity using different methods or instruments than the buyer expects. Agree on the exact testing methodology (Brookfield model, spindle number, RPM, temperature, concentration) in your contract.</li>
          <li><strong>Price volatility</strong> - Guar gum prices can move dramatically based on Indian crop conditions and US drilling activity. Consider annual contracts with quarterly pricing to reduce exposure.</li>
          <li><strong>Moisture absorption</strong> - Guar gum absorbs moisture readily, which can cause caking and viscosity loss. Ensure proper packaging (PE-lined bags) and dry storage conditions.</li>
          <li><strong>Microbiological contamination</strong> - Salmonella in guar gum has caused FDA detentions. Source from facilities with proper sanitation and testing programs.</li>
          <li><strong>Oil and gas grade vs food grade</strong> - These are different products with different quality standards and pricing. Do not use oil and gas grade guar gum in food applications, and do not overpay food-grade prices for industrial use.</li>
          <li><strong>Dioxin contamination</strong> - In 2007, guar gum contaminated with dioxins caused a major EU food scare. While this was an isolated incident, some buyers now require dioxin testing. Be prepared if your buyer requests this.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">How Origin Direct Makes This Easy</h2>
        <p>
          Origin Direct sources guar gum from established processors across Rajasthan and Gujarat, covering food-grade, industrial-grade, and specialty applications. We manage quality control at the processing facility, verify viscosity and specifications using standardized testing protocols, and prepare complete export documentation. Our team coordinates shipping from Mundra and JNPT to US ports and provides the FSVP-compatible records that US food importers need. Whether you need 1 container or a 12-month supply contract, we provide consistent quality at competitive Indian prices.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12">
        <QuoteForm />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
